A .NET team wants to run a one-time workflow 3 hours from now without creating a persistent Schedule. They write the following code:

```csharp
var handle = await client.StartWorkflowAsync(
    (MyWorkflow wf) => wf.RunAsync(),
    new(id: "my-workflow-id", taskQueue: "my-task-queue")
    {
        StartDelay = TimeSpan.FromHours(3),
    });
```

A senior engineer reviews this and says 'This is functionally correct but has a subtle operational difference from using a Schedule that will matter if workers are deployed or the Temporal service is restarted before the 3-hour window elapses.' What is the operational distinction they are referring to?
